The Oxford Dictionary of English Surnames has both.

For "Snow," it has citations starting in 1221, and says "From Old
English 'snaw', snow, a nickname for someone with white hair.

For "Snowball," citations begin 1301 Robert Snawbal. From "OE snaw,
Middle English snow and ME ball, 'a white streak, a bald place," a
nickname for one with a snow-white patch of hair, or, possibly, with a
whitish bald spot amid jetblack hair."

--
Best -- Donna Richoux
